<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-06-18T18:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-06-18T18:00:00-05:00" n="711" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d711">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">124.9318/187: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-06-18T19:00:00-04:00">June 18, 1935—7
                                p.m.</date></dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>170. Your 279, June 15, 2 p.m.<note n="24" xml:id="d711fn24">Not
                                printed.</note> The Department in reply to inquiries <pb facs="0813" n="701" xml:id="pg_701"/> from the press has stated that there has
                            been no consideration nor discussion here in regard to the removal of
                            American troops from Peiping and Tientsin.</p>
                        <p>There has been no press inquiry in regard to the removal of the
                                Legation.<note n="25" xml:id="d711fn25">See section entitled,
                                “Raising of the American Legation in China to the Status of Embassy
                                and Abolition of the Consulate General at Nanking,” <ref target="#pg_508">pp. 508</ref> ff.</note></p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>